equation_narrative.headline: Aromatic context from structural contacts drives confident tyrosine prediction
equation_narrative.story: The model assembles a representation of position 59 by reading structural contacts and local sequence context through layers 1-23, with the representation character shifting from polar (serine-leaning at L0) through hydrophobic aliphatics (valine, leucine, alanine dominate L5-22) to aromatic-compatible by L23. The perception phase gathers evidence that this position sits in an environment requiring a large, aromatic residue. At L25, tyrosine-specific prediction channels activate decisively, and the model commits with 95.84% confidence by L33. MLP neurons in L27-30 provide the strongest support, with multiple Y-enriched features firing simultaneously.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 assemble a representation of position 59's biochemical context through structural and local sequence reading. The model reads 2 structural contacts and 3 co-evolving positions, with attention heads at L12-13 showing the strongest information flow (head L12:2 projects +2.05 toward Y). Early layers show high activation of general positional features (F1:5480, F1:9146 with ~45 projection), while mid-layers develop more specific context. The logit-lens trajectory reflects evolving representation character: initially polar-leaning (S at 22.6% at L0), shifting through hydrophobic aliphatics (V, L, A dominate L5-22 with 15-29% each), and becoming aromatic-compatible by L23 (Y rises to 19.84%, C to 17.67%). This progression reflects the model encoding 'what chemistry fits here' rather than making predictions.
perception_phase.context_character: By L23, the representation encodes an aromatic-compatible environment with moderate burial, consistent with ubiquitin's structural requirements. The local sequence context (RTLSD[Y]NIQKE) provides charged neighbors (D58, N60, K62) that can accommodate a polar aromatic residue.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 2 positions within contact distance, read primarily through attention heads at L12-14
Co-evolutionary signal: 3 coupled positions provide functional constraints on this site
Local sequence: charged neighbors (D58, N60) and hydrophobic context (L57) shape representation through L1-18
L13 velocity: +3.14 total delta driven by attention (+2.90), marking shift toward aromatic character
L18 features: F18:9851 and F18:4071 (21.7, 21.4 proj) encode mid-layer contextual abstraction

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes at L25 when tyrosine overtakes leucine (23.0% vs 22.3%) and Y-specific prediction channels activate. MLP neurons in L27-30 provide decisive support: N27:2890 projects 0.67 toward Y, N29:4973 projects 0.88, and N30:3408 projects 0.86. By L29, tyrosine reaches 73.22% as multiple high-enrichment features fire simultaneously (F30:3888, F30:2419 with 30.7 and 26.2 projection). The final layers L31-33 refine the prediction to 95.84%, with attention heads at L32-33 performing final erasure of competing candidates (C drops from 34.02% peak to 1.79%).
decision_phase.transition: At L23-25, the representation transitions from encoding context to committing to tyrosine. L24 features show moderate Y-specificity (F24:7582, F24:10103 with 9.8, 8.5 proj), while L25 MLP neurons begin casting strong Y-specific votes (N25:2488 projects 0.51, N25:2078 projects 0.50). The lead change at L25 marks the shift from perception to decision.

candidates.narrative: Tyrosine emerges as the clear winner at L25 and dominates through L33. The decision phase is driven by highly specific MLP neurons: N27:2890 (0.67 proj), N29:4973 (0.88 proj), and N30:3408 (0.86 proj) all vote strongly for Y. Late-layer SAE features show extreme Y-specificity: F30:3888 (30.7 proj), F30:2419 (26.2 proj), and F33:7561 (94.3 proj) form a decisive prediction channel. Y rises from 19.84% at L23 to 73.22% at L29 to final 95.84%, reflecting the model's high confidence in the aromatic context it has assembled.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges at L25, reaches 73% by L29, final 95.84% at L33
key_evidence: N29:4973 (0.88 proj) — strong Y voter with T/N cross-talk
F30:3888 (MLP, 30.7 proj) — high-specificity Y prediction channel
F33:7561 (attn, 94.3 proj) — final-layer Y commitment feature
L28 velocity: +7.6 total delta (both attn +3.95 and MLP +3.66) toward Y

candidates.narrative: Cysteine emerges as a late contender, peaking at 34.02% at L31 before being suppressed to 1.79% by final attention erasure. C tracks closely with Y through the perception phase (17.67% at L23 vs Y's 19.84%), suggesting the representation encodes features compatible with both aromatic and sulfur-containing residues. However, C lacks strong MLP support in the decision phase and is actively erased by attention heads at L32-33 (head L32:12 projects -2.32, primarily from local context).
candidates.key_layers: Rises L23-31, peaks at 34.02% (L31), erased L32-33
key_evidence: Peaks at L31 (34.02%) but lacks sustained MLP support
L32 attention erasure: heads 0, 12, 5 collectively project -6.5 away from answer
No high-enrichment C-specific features fire in L30-33

candidates.narrative: Histidine shows moderate support through the decision phase, peaking at 12.8% at L29 before declining to 1.09%. H benefits from some shared aromatic/polar character with Y, and several MLP neurons show H as a secondary vote (N26:1006 projects 0.72 to Y but 0.71 to H). However, H lacks the decisive late-layer feature support that Y receives, and is outcompeted once Y-specific channels fully activate at L29-30.
candidates.key_layers: Moderate through L23-29, peaks 12.8% at L29
key_evidence: N26:1006 shows Y/H ambiguity (0.72 vs 0.71 proj)
Peaks at L29 (12.8%) but drops sharply as Y-specific features dominate

candidates.narrative: Serine leads at L0 with 22.59%, reflecting the embedding's initial polar bias before any contextual processing. This is purely a representation artifact — the embedding space projects toward small polar residues before the model reads structural context. S declines rapidly through L1-8 as the model incorporates information about the aromatic environment, dropping to 4.3% by L8 and remaining suppressed throughout the decision phase.
candidates.key_layers: Leads at L0 (22.59%), declines rapidly L1-8
key_evidence: L0 embedding artifact: 22.59% before any context processing
Rapid decline L1-8 as structural/aromatic context accumulates

candidates.narrative: Leucine dominates the mid-perception phase (L3-22), peaking at 22.3% at L22. The logit lens projects toward L because the representation at these layers encodes hydrophobic character from local sequence context (L57 adjacent) and general burial features. This is not a prediction — it reflects that the model is assembling a 'hydrophobic-compatible' representation before refining to the specific aromatic requirement. L is decisively outcompeted when Y-specific channels activate at L25.
candidates.key_layers: Dominates L3-22, peaks 22.3% at L22, overtaken L25
key_evidence: Leads L15-22 during hydrophobic representation phase
Loses to Y at L25 when aromatic-specific features activate

turning_points.description: The representation shifts from generic positional encoding to context-specific features. L12 head 2 writes strongly (+2.05 proj) with minimal structural/coevol attention (0.001, 0.001), suggesting abstract feature composition. L13 shows +3.14 velocity driven by attention (+2.90), with MLP neurons like N12:1529 (0.73 proj toward Y) beginning to encode aromatic preference. The logit lens still shows hydrophobic aliphatics (A, K, L cycling through leads), but the underlying representation is accumulating aromatic-compatible features.

The perception-to-decision transition occurs here. L23 shows the representation is aromatic-compatible (Y at 19.84%, C at 17.67%) but not yet committed. L24 features begin showing Y-specificity (F24:7582, F24:10103), and L25 MLP neurons cast decisive Y votes (N25:2488 projects 0.51, N25:2078 projects 0.50, total layer MLP proj +1.72). The lead change at L25 (Y overtakes L, 23.0% vs 22.3%) marks the shift from 'what context is here' to 'tyrosine is the answer'.

The decision solidifies through massive MLP support. L27 contributes +3.65 total (MLP neurons N27:2890, N27:3776 project 0.67, 0.59). L28 adds +7.6 (both attn +3.95 and MLP +3.66). L29 contributes +2.21 via MLP (N29:4973 projects 0.88, N29:630 projects 0.66). L30 features show extreme Y-specificity: F30:3888 (30.7 proj), F30:2419 (26.2 proj), F30:6262 (25.4 proj). Y rises from 23% at L25 to 73.22% at L29, with competing candidates (C, H) peaking briefly but lacking sustained support.

deep_dives.label: Structural reading L12-14
deep_dives.caption: L12-14 attention heads read structural contacts and compose abstract features. Head L12:2 projects +2.05 toward Y with minimal structural attention (0.001), suggesting feature composition rather than direct contact reading. L13 velocity (+3.14, attn-driven) marks the shift toward aromatic representation character.

deep_dives.label: Early context features L1-18
deep_dives.caption: Early SAE features encode positional and contextual information. L1 features (F1:5480, F1:9146 with ~45 proj) represent general position encoding. L9 features show refined context. L18 features (F18:9851, F18:4071 with 21.7, 21.4 proj) encode mid-layer abstraction before decision channels activate.

deep_dives.label: Perception→Decision L24-25
deep_dives.caption: L24-25 marks the transition from context encoding to prediction. L24 MLP contributes +1.93 with neurons like N24:882 (0.36 proj) and N24:4679 (0.35 proj) beginning Y-specific voting. L25 MLP adds +1.72 with N25:2488 (0.51 proj) and N25:2078 (0.50 proj) casting decisive votes. The lead change at L25 (Y overtakes L) reflects this shift.

deep_dives.label: Decision MLP neurons L27-30
deep_dives.caption: L27-30 MLP neurons provide the decisive evidence for tyrosine. N27:2890 (0.67 proj), N29:4973 (0.88 proj), and N30:3408 (0.86 proj) are strong Y voters. Total MLP contribution across these layers: +10.8. These neurons encode the final integration of aromatic context with specific Y identity.

deep_dives.label: Y-specific channels L30-33
deep_dives.caption: Late-layer SAE features show extreme Y-specificity. L30: F30:3888 (30.7 proj), F30:2419 (26.2 proj), F30:6262 (25.4 proj) form a strong prediction channel. L33: F33:7561 (94.3 proj), F33:4166 (93.7 proj), F33:6423 (93.6 proj) represent final commitment. These features have high Y-enrichment and fire specifically for aromatic predictions.

deep_dives.label: Competitor erasure L32-33
deep_dives.caption: L32-33 attention heads perform final erasure of competing candidates. L32 heads project -2.41, -2.32, -1.78 away from Y, primarily erasing C (which peaked at 34.02% at L31). L33 head activity projects -7.42 via attention, suppressing residual C and H probability to finalize 95.84% confidence in Y.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts tyrosine with 95.84% confidence by assembling a representation of position 59's aromatic-compatible environment through structural contacts, co-evolutionary constraints, and local sequence context. The perception phase (L1-23) encodes the biochemical requirements — a large, polar-aromatic residue compatible with charged neighbors (D58, N60) and moderate burial. The decision phase (L25-33) activates Y-specific prediction channels through MLP neurons (N27:2890, N29:4973, N30:3408) and high-enrichment SAE features (F30:3888, F33:7561). The strongest evidence is the coordinated activation of multiple Y-specific features at L30 (total MLP proj +3.22) combined with systematic erasure of the cysteine alternative at L32-33, reflecting the model's confidence that the aromatic ring is essential for this position's function in ubiquitin.
